    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. so basically keep the core tight and the spine stiff. i also noticed that when i'm at the bottom of the lift, my shoulders feel like they're rounding forward a bit too much. is that part of the issue with the back pain? how do i keep my upper back and lats engaged so i don't collapse forward?",
      "source": "evaluator",
      "targeted_response_start": "",
      "beast_baseline": "got it. so basically keep the core tight and the spine stiff. i also noticed that when i'm at the bottom of the lift, my shoulders feel like they're rounding forward a bit too much. is that part of the issue with the back pain? how do i keep my upper back and lats engaged so i don't collapse forward?",
      "beast_suffix": "",
      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, your shoulders rounding forward is definitely part of the issue, as it forces your spine into flexion and takes the load off your legs, making your back feel like it's doing the work. To fix this, you need to actively pull your shoulder blades down and back, squeezing them together as if someone is about to pinch your upper back with a giant pair of pliers. This action will engage your lats and upper back, creating a stable platform for your legs to push against. Think of your upper body as a rigid tower that must not sway, while your hips act as the engine driving the movement. If your shoulders collapse, you are essentially asking your spine to hold the weight instead of your legs.",
      "source": "target",
